{"schema": {"fields":[{"type":"integer","name":"index"},{"type":"string","name":"author_association"},{"type":"string","name":"body"},{"type":"datetime","name":"created_at"},{"type":"string","name":"html_url"},{"type":"integer","name":"id"},{"type":"string","name":"issue_url"},{"type":"string","name":"node_id"},{"type":"datetime","name":"updated_at"},{"type":"string","name":"url"},{"type":"string","name":"user"}],"pandas_version":"0.20.0","primaryKey":["index"]}, "data": [{"index":0,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"Ah, whole particle situation is currently quite a mess (`Particle` is `CanvasRenderer`-only, `Sprite` and `ParticleSystem` are `WebGLRenderer`-only). \n\nThere are multiple approaches because unfortunately implementation details matter and yes, there are big performance differences (range is from few thousand to million elements depending on which features you want and how it's implemented).\n\nShort answer: the best approach with current three.js for doing \"classical\" particle engine with emitters and life cycles is probably `ParticleSystem` with custom attributes and custom shaders, playing with particles from fixed \"pool\". \n\nI already did some examples with per-particle size and color changes via custom attributes. What would be needed are then texture atlases with some indexing for sprite evolution \/ varied per-particle look and some management of behaviors \/ life-cycle either in JavaScript or in shaders. Probably easier to start in JS, just treat WebGL as dumb renderer and then when seeing more of what's going on trying to move common patterns into shaders.\n\nAnyways, particles are very rich topic, another rabbit hole ;) This is something I planned to look into more properly already since quite some time.\n","created_at":"2011-07-24T22:24:28.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/375#issuecomment-1642446","id":1642446,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/375","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE2NDI0NDY=","updated_at":"2011-07-24T22:24:28.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/1642446","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alteredq\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alteredq\/events{\/privacy}","avatar_url":"https:\/\/avatars2.githubusercontent.com\/u\/438022?v=4","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alteredq","gists_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alteredq\/gists{\/gist_id}","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/alteredq","subscriptions_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alteredq\/subscriptions","node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjQzODAyMg==","repos_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alteredq\/repos","received_events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alteredq\/received_events","gravatar_id":"","starred_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alteredq\/starred{\/owner}{\/repo}","site_admin":false,"login":"alteredq","type":"User","id":438022,"followers_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alteredq\/followers","organizations_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/alteredq\/orgs"}},{"index":1,"author_association":"CONTRIBUTOR","body":"thanks for the detailed reply again @alteredq :) \n\nideally a particle engine would be able to handle rendering of different particles (2d, 3d, webgl, canvas) \n\nbut yes, its another interesting topic, and i'm tempted to dive into this once i'm done with the geometry parts :)\n","created_at":"2011-07-26T08:07:59.000Z","html_url":"https:\/\/github.com\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/375#issuecomment-1652439","id":1652439,"issue_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/375","node_id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE2NTI0Mzk=","updated_at":"2011-07-26T08:07:59.000Z","url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/repos\/mrdoob\/three.js\/issues\/comments\/1652439","user":{"following_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/zz85\/following{\/other_user}","events_url":"https:\/\/api.github.com\/users\/zz85\/eve